` relates to the elements of `xs`. The provided code does not establish this correctly.\n\nThe error arises from an unproven assumption within the inductive step of `List.reverseRecOn`. To fix this, we need to rethink the definition of `restrict_tree`.\n\nInstead of trying to prove the complex membership condition for `xs ++ [A] ∈ S.pre.subtree` (which is `List.reverseRecOn.inl (S.pre.subtree_incl ...) (choose_pair ...) ...`), we can directly construct the proof of membership in the target tree.\n\nThe target is to show that for any `y` in the `subtree` of the `restrict` strategy, `y` is also in the `subtree` of the original strategy `S`.\n\nA correct approach would be:\n```tactics\ndef restrict_tree (x : S.pre.subtree) : (restrict hWV hW S).pre.subtree :=\n  -- Goal: x ∈ (Strategy.pre (@restrict X V W hWV hW p S)).subtree\n  -- This means x is a list of moves starting from some position in S's tree\n  -- We know x is a list of moves in S's tree (x ∈ S.pre.subtree)\n  -- We need to show that these moves are valid in the restricted game\n  -- This involves showing that for each move A in x, there exists a corresponding move B in W such that B ⊆ A\n  -- This is exactly what `hW` provides\n  -- We can construct the proof using `List.reverseRecOn` but need to handle the induction differently\n  -- or more directly, use the fact that `x ∈ S.pre.subtree` implies the existence of a path in the original game\n  -- which can be shown to correspond to a path in the restricted game\n  -- The simplest way is to show that the preconditions for `x` in the restricted game are satisfied\n  -- This is equivalent to showing that for each move A in x, `A ∈ W` and `A` is a subset of some move in the original game\n  -- This is exactly what `hW` gives us\n  -- We can use the fact that `x ∈ S.pre.subtree` implies `x` is a valid sequence of moves in the original game\n  -- and then show this implies validity in the restricted game\n  -- This can be done by induction on the structure of x 