      "\n        ), sorry⟩",
      "s\ndef restrict_tree (x : S.pre.subtree) : (restrict hWV hW S).pre.subtree :=\n    List.reverseRecOn x.val ⟨[], by simp [nil_mem_chainTree]⟩ fun xs A ys ↦ --TODO need to distingush parity\n        ⟨chainTree.concat W (PreStrategy.subtree_incl _ ys) (choose_pair hW A) (by\n        simp\n        have : xs ++ [A] ∈ S.pre.subtree := by sorry --TODO need tree reverseRecOn here´\n        have h := this.1\n        rw [concat_mem_chainTree] at h\n        intro _; apply (choose_pair_sub hW A).trans\n        --TODO need ys restrict to xs here\n        sorry), sorry⟩\n```\n\nThe issue is within the `List.reverseRecOn` definition. `List.reverseRecOn` is a function that performs a recursive proof over a list structure. The specific error occurs when trying to prove that `xs ++ [A]` is in the preimage of the strategy `S`.\n\nThe code attempts to prove `xs ++ [A] ∈ S.pre.subtree` using `by sorry`. A `sorry` tactic is used when a proof is incomplete or when a placeholder is needed. In this context, `xs ++ [A] ∈ S.pre.subtree` is a proposition that should be proven. Using `sorry` means this proposition is not proven.\n\nThe proof state at this point is:\n- `x : S.pre.subtree` (the input to `restrict_tree`)\n- `xs : List ↑V` (the list being built by `reverseRecOn`)\n- `A : ↑V` (the value being appended to `xs`)\n- `ys : ↥(Strategy.pre (@restrict X V W hWV hW p S)).subtree` (the list that `xs` is being reversed into)\n\nThe goal is to show that `xs ++ [A]` is in the preimage of `S`. This is a necessary step for `reverseRecOn` to work correctly, as it needs to know that the list it's processing is valid according to the strategy `S`.\n\nThe overall proof strategy is to define a new strategy `R := restrict hWV hW S` and then prove properties about its preimage `R.pre.subtree`. The `restrict_tree` lemma is intended to establish a relationship between `S.pre.subtree` and `R.pre.subtree`.\n\nSpecifically, `restrict_tree` aims to show that for any `x` in `S.pre.subtree`, the reversed